***Follow up actions added to [8\. Follow-ups](#bookmark=kix.v8569zbkmbr2)***

### Summary (w/c 17.11.2025)

**Order Volume declined for the first time in W12 (-9% WoW) to 5,532 orders, with GTV \-10% WoW. Our platform penetration (orders in FTT zones during window) decreased to 2.20% (-0.3ppt WoW). We are attributing this to the following factors:**

* **Both Carousel** **and Mission Tile were unpinned in favour of other business priorities (Ad revenue, Black Friday respectively) leading to \-55% traffic decline. These two merchandising elements are our largest two entry points. We will resume Mission Tile pinning after BF ends.**   
* **Despite this, new Px onboarding improved selection from 4 \> 10 Px Seen in Dublin, and drove \+39% WoW OV growth to 110 orders.**

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=kix.lu2neio3woks) 

* **Key flag is that OV has fallen, driven by reduced visibility of FTT, which has caused declines in both FTT visibility and collection-page engagement (this decline has been partially \- but not fully \- offset by increased conversion).**  
  * FTT visibility (users exposed to FTT proposition[^1]) dropped 55% this week (0.81m from 1.81m), driven by the unpinning of the Mission Tile and Home Carousel \- which meant that the percentage of FTT sessions that saw a FTT entry point dropped from from 75% to 13% for Mission Tile, and from 23% to 4% for Home Carousel.  
  * With fewer users exposed to  FTT, FTT engagement also declined \- evidenced by collection traffic (a strong proxy for engagement, as most users navigate through the collection page) falling by 42%. For context, the Mission Tile and Home Carousel have typically driven 71% of traffic into the FTT funnel.  
  * Conversion rate increased (96%) partially offsetting the impact on OV \- driven by the large decrease in total sessions, which overshadowed the relatively smaller change in conversions.  
* **This suggests that visibility remains key:** many users still havenâ€™t seen the proposition enough to engage. Abs cx numbers have fallen for the fourth consecutive week (2.9k this week vs. 3.5k, 3.7k, and 3.7k in the prior 3 weeks), underscoring the need to increase exposure and drive trial.  
* **Once cx engage with the proposition, indicators of its appeal are positive:**  
  * Returning-to-FTT customer share and OV share continue to grow, demonstrating stickiness among existing users (though this needs to be balanced against the decreasing abs number of New-to-FTT cx).  
  * Ratings remain steady at 4.36 (vs. 4.35 last week), showing consistent satisfaction.  
  * â€œWho Loves Itâ€ analysis confirms broad appeal across demographics, indicating the FTT offering resonates widely once experienced.  
* **Other notes:**  
  * **We successfully deepened supply this week \-** adding 59 additional sites across UKI (including from existing brands \- such as Wagamama (+13 sites), LEON (+6 sites) and Farmer J (+4 sites), as well as new brands in Dublin). Abs OV in Ireland has grown in response (Dublin OV up 39% WoW), and share of OV from Ireland and the North has increased.  
  * **New-to-Brand has declined,** continuing a downward trend over the few months \- we will continue to monitor this closely.   
  * **Other indicators remain steady**  
    * Scheduled orders are flat (18% vs 19% last week); top-performing brands, cuisines, and dishes remain consistent, New-to-Roo and family splits remain stable.  
    * High-frequency users continue to dominate.

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=kix.tcvian4nnmoj) 

**Media Insights:** Marketing provided a full channel status update in SteerCo this week, found [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LwTCzVFTyFdY_KWA7X3CJXaJAPe73jnYecq2Ehne3HM/edit?usp=sharing), showing positive signals that customer engagement and resonance with our proposition is either in line with or exceeding benchmark across channels. Adjustments have been made in-flight to ensure spend is maximised, and channel learning from Q4 will be reflected in H1 strategy and deployment of marketing spend.

**CRM:** Last week we launched our first Px solus email featuring wagamama (reach \~1M cx), and as a fallback we had a new inspiration email using our OOH imagery (reach \~0.8M cx). This was our best performing week to date, particularly notable as these communications were not incentivised. Push: 1.1% CTR (vs 0.8% benchmark), driving 154 attributed orders, outperforming previous weeks. Email had a CTR of 0.3%, at benchmark, consistent with recent performance. **Flag:** email reach was impacted this week, as a Black Friday email sent at the same time as our Family Time email, taking away part of the FT audience. 

**DXGY:** Record week for Wave 2, sweeping up an additional \+4.2k entrants, higher than that of any weekly performance to date. 19.3k have entered in total, with 1.3k Cx completing all steps. To date, Â£32.4k vouchers have been earned, with spend at Â£18.6k (vs total budget Â£100k) and redemption rate at 58%.

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=kix.csx7hefa09zy) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=kix.tqffh2sf2jn8)*** 

**B10s:** 

* Lowlights: OI increased \+0.06ppt WoW to 3.01% compared to non-Dinneroo orders, which dropped \-0.25ppt WoW to 1.61%.  
* Highlights: Unacceptable Lates dropped \-1.52ppt WoW to 9.01%, still behind non-dinneroo order performance but better WoW performance. This was driven by RWT reaching its lowest week at 5.70% dropping \-1.20ppt WoW. PEX and Banana Tree reached their lowest OI rates 2.99% & 1.01% respectively. App rating increased \+0.01 pts WoW to 4.36.

**Care:**

* **Claims: PTD** increased vs prior week to 7.46% orders with a claim (+0.06 ppt WoW) and average claim amount at Â£15.65 (+23p WoW), reflecting poorer partner operational performance, with Missing Items remaining the top offender for CCPO at 21p, while Unacceptable Lates (15+ mins) decrease to 2.99%.  
* **63p per Dinneroo order** (-3p WoW), which is **\+53p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+42p above budget** (21p).   
* Commercial focus on bundle improvements to address â€˜One Item Claimsâ€™ equalling Â£25, due to no modifiers. This is actively being explored by Dishoom and Kricket \- two of our three largest contributors, while wagamama plans to review in Q1 2025\.

    * Top 5 brands: Wagamama, Pho, Dishoom, PEX, Banana Tree \- with Wagamama and Pho swapping places this week (Wagamama back in GB)  
    * Top cuisines: Asian dominates (55% vs 53% last week), followed by Indian (14% vs 15% last week) and Italian (11% vs 12% last week)  
    * Top 3 dishes: Wags Family Chicken Katsu, Phoâ€™s Pho the Whole Family and Dishoomâ€™s Chicken Ruby (same as last week)  
* **Cx Composition \-** New-to-Roo is constant, while New-to Brand has declined. OV continues to be driven by high-frequency users, with PLUS users maintaining dominance (up vs last week) and almost 2/3rds of users returning to the platform within 7 days (down vs last week). Returning-to-FTT continues to grow from a cx and OV share perspective, though abs New-to-Roo FTT cx are down.. From a demographic POV, family split remains constant, while share of OV from ROI and the North have increased.  
  * **New-to-Roo Cx:** 1% cx are new-to-platform (vs 1% last week)  
  * **New-to-Brand Cx:** 30% of orders are new to brand (vs 34% last week)  
  * **PLUS / Frequent Cx:** 66% of orders are from PLUS users (vs 64% last week); 61% return to platform within 7 days (vs 63% last week)  
  * **Returning-to-FTT:** Returning-to-FTT cx and OV are up WoW: they accounted for 45% of cx this week (vs 41% last week), and 47% of OV this week (vs 43% last week). However, we are beginning to see a downward trend in abs New-to-Roo FTT cx each week (2.9k this week, 3.5k, 3.7k, 3.7k the 3 weeks before \- which needs to be monitored)

**W/C 24 Nov:** Next week, weâ€™re leading with Px email. Thursdayâ€™s push will serve as a final reminder for customers to enter Family Dinneroo Rewards. This copy has performed well previously, achieving 0.9% CTR.

Continuous improvement: 

* Day-of-week testing (W/C 10/Nov) validated our current communication drumbeat. Tuesday was the optimal day for email sends to optimise CTR and orders. Push performance was the same across days of the week.  
* Further targeting proposal \- exclude tribe segment â€œBig Brand Loyalistâ€ from email from w/c 24/11. We tested for two weeks sending to different tribes to understand CTR and FT conversion. Big Brand loyalist drove 0 orders at a CTR 0.1% for email. Segment size \~153K Cx.    
* Following up on feedback from previous weeks, for the PX email launching on 8.12, we want to identify zones with more PX in the area, and communicate â€œNew in Family Dinnerooâ€ messaging.

Px Ops continued with the same eight partners that are contributing the most to defects in the weekly Operating Theatre. 


* PizzaExpress: OI reached their lowest Dinneroo rate this week at 2.99% (-0.72ppt WoW) vs Non-Dinneroo (2.0%). RWT at 14.4% (+0.4ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (8.70%)  
  * PEX aligning internally on which sites they are suspending (not ops viable) by EoW. No sites added to the proposition in the meantime to help. Continued training and education for key offender sites, especially around problem dishes (pasta/Lasagne). Pasta is the primary driver of RWT issues.  
* Pho: OI 3.84% (+0.76 ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (1.98%). Lowest week of RWT at 4.70% vs non-dinneroo (4.0%)  
  * Pho has held a meeting with all sites to discuss MI and Spillage. They are undertaking staff refresher courses addressing how the bags are packaged to ensure it is consistent across sites.  
  * Test order performed at Manchester site (frequent offender for spilt orders) that resulted in a positive experience with no spills or missed items. Packaging did not include taped lids or cling wrap.  
* Wagamama: OI 3.40% (-0.02 ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (2.06%), RWT 4.50% (-1.30ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (3.60%)  
  * The senior leadership team are aligned with the improvements that need to be made.  
  * Wagamama are exploring redoing photography to improve perception (likely Q1 2026\)  
  * Wagamama are exploring trialling a larger bag to solve the issue of missing items when 2+ items are in the order (as the bags can only fit 1 Dinneroo proposition dish and nothing else). Dates TBC.  
* Banana Tree: Lowest week of OI 1.01%\! (-1.10 ppt WoW) and surpassing non-dinneroo (1.54%). Lowest RWT 4.80% (-2.60ppt WoW) and surpassing non-dinneroo (5.80%).

#### A1) Whole Bundle Claims

Currently, due to bundle design, some of our top OV Partners such as wagamama, Dishoom and Kricket, are receiving whole bundle claims despite the contact reason being missing items, spilled or cooked incorrectly \- which is often only due to a single element of the bundle. With wagamama, this is hard to quantify as portion sizes are not clear, and they do not want to add confusion to their menu flow. Proposition review to be undertaken in early Q1. 

Kricket has fallen out vs last weekâ€™s reporting, as theyâ€™ve temporarily come off the proposition to focus on packaging and will rejoin with updated menu items, removing the â€˜whole bundle claimâ€™ challenge, as they implement modifiers. Dishoom is currently in discussion. Pho not an immediate cause for concern as it has modifiers, and upon investigation, is likely where a customer has not received all elements of the bundle (or is falsely claiming they didnâ€™t).
